1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,634
Previously on Ghost Whisperer...

2
00:00:04,399 --> 00:00:05,298
No!

3
00:00:05,333 --> 00:00:06,866
I'll always love you, Melinda.

4
00:00:06,933 --> 00:00:09,667
Please. not you.

5
00:00:09,732 --> 00:00:10,966
You have to cross over.

6
00:00:11,033 --> 00:00:12,866
I don't want to.

7
00:00:16,099 --> 00:00:17,233
Jim, no!

8
00:00:18,500 --> 00:00:19,699
You're back.

9
00:00:19,766 --> 00:00:21,200
Do I know you?

10
00:00:21,266 --> 00:00:22,816
I see the same guy that you see,

11
00:00:22,851 --> 00:00:24,366
Different hair, nose, eyes.

12
00:00:24,433 --> 00:00:26,866
It's not Jim. he's in there somewhere.

13
00:00:26,933 --> 00:00:28,567
He just has to be.

14
00:00:28,633 --> 00:00:29,682
You're not gonna tell me that you think

15
00:00:29,717 --> 00:00:30,732
I'm your husband reincarnated.

16
00:00:30,799 --> 00:00:33,433
Because you're the only sane
person I've met since I woke up.

17
00:00:33,500 --> 00:00:36,200
It's not much. but maybe you
can help me finish my garage.

18
00:00:36,266 --> 00:00:37,766
And you could live there
while you do the work.

19
00:00:37,832 --> 00:00:40,033
Just until you figure
out your next move.

20
00:00:40,099 --> 00:00:41,366
Do you know how lucky you are?

21
00:00:41,433 --> 00:00:44,699
You are gonna get a second
shot at your one true love.

22
00:00:44,766 --> 00:00:46,866
That's strange. I've
been hoping for a clue,

23
00:00:46,933 --> 00:00:48,699
Something to tell me who I was.

24
00:00:48,766 --> 00:00:50,999
Guess I got more than I bargained for.

25
00:00:51,066 --> 00:00:52,866
I bought that less than a month ago.

26
00:00:52,933 --> 00:00:56,066
Question is... who did I buy it for?

27
00:01:18,266 --> 00:01:19,766
Hey!

28
00:01:19,832 --> 00:01:21,567
Hey. you're looking
chipper this morning.

29
00:01:21,633 --> 00:01:23,799
That's how a morning off effects me.

30
00:01:23,866 --> 00:01:25,133
Oh, yeah. you got a little...

31
00:01:26,266 --> 00:01:27,966
- Thank you.
- Yeah, sure.

32
00:01:28,033 --> 00:01:30,133
Where you running off to?

33
00:01:30,200 --> 00:01:33,600
The farmer's market. we're supposed
to meet Delia there at 9:00.

34
00:01:33,667 --> 00:01:35,466
We are?

35
00:01:35,533 --> 00:01:38,933
Oh, that's right.

36
00:01:38,999 --> 00:01:43,200
Melinda, I'm so sorry. I gotta do a job.

37
00:01:43,266 --> 00:01:46,866
Yeah... yeah. anything interesting?

38
00:01:46,933 --> 00:01:51,099
Well, if you call making kitchen
cabinets interesting, then yeah.

39
00:01:51,166 --> 00:01:54,466
Cabinets are great. I
mean, I love cabinets.

40
00:01:57,400 --> 00:02:00,333
You found that... that ring...

41
00:02:00,400 --> 00:02:02,799
Did you ever look into it?

42
00:02:03,933 --> 00:02:05,999
Right. yeah.

43
00:02:06,066 --> 00:02:07,133
- The ring...
- Right.

44
00:02:07,200 --> 00:02:09,300
Did you find out anything?

45
00:02:11,866 --> 00:02:15,233
You don't want to know. sorry.

46
00:02:17,933 --> 00:02:21,667
Of course I want to know.
that's all I want... is to know.

47
00:02:21,732 --> 00:02:23,966
Charlie used to say that. drove me nuts.

48
00:02:24,033 --> 00:02:26,366
Jim never did. because Jim
was never a question dodger.

49
00:02:26,433 --> 00:02:28,699
What does that even mean,
"you don't want to know"?

50
00:02:28,766 --> 00:02:31,667
Well, with Charlie it either meant
that he didn't want to talk about it,

51
00:02:31,732 --> 00:02:33,366
Or he didn't want me to talk about it,

52
00:02:33,433 --> 00:02:36,933
Or that he actually wanted to
talk, but wasn't sure if I did.

53
00:02:36,999 --> 00:02:38,200
Well, thank you. that's helpful.

54
00:02:38,266 --> 00:02:40,233
So, what do you think Sammeant?

55
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:41,781
What else could he mean?

56
00:02:41,816 --> 00:02:43,333
He found her... his girlfriend,

57
00:02:43,400 --> 00:02:45,466
His soon-to-be
future wife.

58
00:02:45,533 --> 00:02:46,766
That's why he blew me off today.

59
00:02:46,832 --> 00:02:48,567
That's why he's been
so distracted lately.

60
00:02:48,633 --> 00:02:49,832
Because he found her.

61
00:02:49,899 --> 00:02:51,133
And he's probably gonna get on a plane.

62
00:02:51,200 --> 00:02:52,732
He's gonna fly all the
way to Michigan or Paris

63
00:02:52,799 --> 00:02:54,433
Or wherever it is she is right now.

64
00:02:54,500 --> 00:02:57,166
Mel, I seriously doubt that Jim's spirit

65
00:02:57,233 --> 00:03:00,233
Would have gone through all the
trouble of taking over Sam's body

66
00:03:00,300 --> 00:03:02,933
Just to run off with another woman.

67
00:03:04,033 --> 00:03:05,433
Please tell me nobody heard me say that.

68
00:03:05,500 --> 00:03:07,333
Yeah. but he doesn't
even know that he's Jim.

69
00:03:07,400 --> 00:03:09,732
I mean, what if he smells her perfume

70
00:03:09,799 --> 00:03:12,533
And he gets confused or attracted or...

71
00:03:12,600 --> 00:03:14,300
Honey, you are spinning.

72
00:03:14,366 --> 00:03:17,567
I wouldn't have to if he
wasn't dodging my questions.

73
00:03:18,433 --> 00:03:19,966
It's just too loaded.

74
00:03:20,033 --> 00:03:21,600
I mean, I don't know
how to approach it...

75
00:03:21,667 --> 00:03:23,033
Oh, you could.

76
00:03:23,099 --> 00:03:24,567
That's perfect!

77
00:03:24,633 --> 00:03:27,899
It's not perfect. it's bruised.

78
00:03:27,966 --> 00:03:30,633
They all are. see?

79
00:03:31,832 --> 00:03:33,300
No, not again!

80
00:03:33,366 --> 00:03:34,533
I'm sorry. did I do that?

81
00:03:34,600 --> 00:03:36,099
No, it happens all the time.

82
00:03:36,166 --> 00:03:37,166
And you wonder why?

83
00:03:37,233 --> 00:03:39,033
Well if I could get
some help around here!

84
00:03:39,099 --> 00:03:41,033
I need to get home and cook dinner.

85
00:03:41,099 --> 00:03:42,066
Well, maybe I can help you.

86
00:03:43,300 --> 00:03:45,200
Oh thank god, finally
somebody with manners!

87
00:03:45,266 --> 00:03:46,566
You know I have been
coming here every Saturday

88
00:03:46,601 --> 00:03:47,866
for God knows how long,

89
00:03:47,933 --> 00:03:51,366
All of a sudden he decides to ignore me.

90
00:03:51,433 --> 00:03:53,799
I don't you how long I've been waiting.

91
00:03:53,866 --> 00:03:55,799
How long do you think?

92
00:03:55,866 --> 00:03:59,133
I... I'm not sure.

93
00:04:00,633 --> 00:04:02,799
Let me guess, a ghost wants pie?

94
00:04:02,866 --> 00:04:04,431
I'm not sure what she wants.

95
00:04:04,466 --> 00:04:06,066
I don't even think she knows she's dead.

96
00:04:06,133 --> 00:04:07,832
Wait!

97
00:04:07,899 --> 00:04:12,999
Could I,get 4 of those? thank you.

98
00:04:13,066 --> 00:04:15,866
They're for you. maybe I
could give you a ride home.

99
00:04:15,933 --> 00:04:18,999
Oh, that's so sweet. thank you.

100
00:04:19,066 --> 00:04:21,567
My name is Tammy. Tammy Gardner.

101
00:04:21,633 --> 00:04:24,667
You... you did get the
organic ones, right?

102
00:04:24,732 --> 00:04:28,300
You know what, I better go and check.

103
00:04:28,366 --> 00:04:31,233
Did you just offer to give
a ride home to a ghost?

104
00:04:31,300 --> 00:04:33,732
Only because she doesn't
realize that she's dead.

105
00:04:37,166 --> 00:04:38,300
Hi.

106
00:04:38,366 --> 00:04:40,866
Hi, I'm Melinda Gordon.
Are you Mr. Gardner?

107
00:04:40,933 --> 00:04:43,181
Yes, I am. I'm sorry.

108
00:04:43,216 --> 00:04:45,500
Like I tell all you
realtors, we're not selling.

109
00:04:45,567 --> 00:04:48,366
Actually, I'm here about your wife.

110
00:04:48,433 --> 00:04:52,999
My wife? oh, she's not
here. she's at the market.

111
00:04:54,099 --> 00:04:55,567
Did something happen?

112
00:04:55,633 --> 00:04:57,899
How long ago did she leave?

113
00:04:57,966 --> 00:05:00,066
Over an hour ago. she was due back...

114
00:05:00,133 --> 00:05:02,466
Ah, there she is now!

115
00:05:04,066 --> 00:05:05,667
Hey, sweetheart.

116
00:05:08,500 --> 00:05:09,500
Who's she?

117
00:05:09,567 --> 00:05:11,166
I was getting worried.

118
00:05:11,233 --> 00:05:13,667
Melinda, this is my wife, Elizabeth.

119
00:05:13,732 --> 00:05:15,433
Unless you two know each other?

120
00:05:15,500 --> 00:05:16,600
No.

121
00:05:16,667 --> 00:05:19,999
No, the thing is I own
an antique store in town,

122
00:05:20,066 --> 00:05:22,699
And someone left a vase on consignment,

123
00:05:22,766 --> 00:05:25,533
And I was just trying to track her down.

124
00:05:25,600 --> 00:05:29,333
Hmm. that wasn't me. I'm sorry.

125
00:05:31,033 --> 00:05:33,866
You know, just so there are no mix-ups,

126
00:05:33,933 --> 00:05:36,681
The woman who left the vase,

127
00:05:36,716 --> 00:05:39,500
Her name was Tammy... Tammy Gardner.

128
00:05:40,699 --> 00:05:42,633
Tammy, um...

129
00:05:42,699 --> 00:05:46,466
Tammy was my first wife. we're divorced.

130
00:05:46,533 --> 00:05:50,699
Oh. you wouldn't have a recent
address change for her maybe?

131
00:05:50,766 --> 00:05:52,466
No, I'm sorry.

132
00:05:52,533 --> 00:05:56,066
I haven't heard from her since
she walked out on me 2 years ago.

133
00:05:57,233 --> 00:05:59,033
Wish I could've been more help.

134
00:05:59,099 --> 00:06:00,433
Good day.

135
00:06:57,099 --> 00:06:59,399
Hi. I'm sorry to bother you.

136
00:06:59,466 --> 00:07:02,032
But I went by your
store. but it was closed.

137
00:07:02,099 --> 00:07:03,700
And your address was listed...

138
00:07:03,766 --> 00:07:05,132
So is my phone number.

139
00:07:05,199 --> 00:07:06,366
I know, I'm sorry.

140
00:07:06,433 --> 00:07:08,766
I wanted to see to you in person.

141
00:07:08,833 --> 00:07:11,600
I need you to tell me what
you know about my wife.

142
00:07:17,333 --> 00:07:18,867
When exactly did she leave?

143
00:07:18,933 --> 00:07:22,900
Just about 2 years ago, October 15.

144
00:07:22,967 --> 00:07:25,700
I remember that day because
it was our fourth anniversary.

145
00:07:25,766 --> 00:07:27,600
At first I wasn't worried.

146
00:07:27,666 --> 00:07:30,166
She'd disappeared before.
sort of a pattern for her.

147
00:07:30,233 --> 00:07:32,833
But she'd always come back
after a couple of days.

148
00:07:32,900 --> 00:07:36,066
When she didn't show up after 3 days,

149
00:07:36,132 --> 00:07:38,099
I knew something was wrong.

150
00:07:38,166 --> 00:07:40,999
I just can't understand
why she hasn't contacted me.

151
00:07:41,033 --> 00:07:43,966
You said this was a
pattern? her disappearing?

152
00:07:44,033 --> 00:07:46,600
Maybe in a way it's good
she hasn't contacted me.

153
00:07:46,667 --> 00:07:49,233
Means she's probably
staying out of trouble.

154
00:07:49,300 --> 00:07:51,200
What kind of trouble?

155
00:07:51,266 --> 00:07:53,567
She had mood swings.

156
00:07:53,633 --> 00:07:54,667
What did she do?

157
00:07:54,733 --> 00:07:57,900
She couldn't stand feeling confined.

158
00:07:57,966 --> 00:08:00,733
She'd run away, then come back,

159
00:08:00,800 --> 00:08:03,099
Looking disheveled and confused.

160
00:08:03,166 --> 00:08:05,934
That doesn't sound at
all like the Tammy I met.

161
00:08:05,999 --> 00:08:07,700
That's part of the illness.

162
00:08:07,767 --> 00:08:10,467
I mean, she could be
delightful and happy one day,

163
00:08:10,533 --> 00:08:12,800
And then... and then
depressed and angry the next.

164
00:08:12,867 --> 00:08:13,900
Was she ever diagnosed?

165
00:08:13,966 --> 00:08:16,233
Oh, no. no. she refused to see a doctor.

166
00:08:16,300 --> 00:08:18,633
I talked to plenty myself.

167
00:08:18,700 --> 00:08:21,900
Said it was some sort
of bipolar disorder.

168
00:08:24,533 --> 00:08:25,900
I loved her so much.

169
00:08:25,966 --> 00:08:28,900
But it's so painful living with someone

170
00:08:28,966 --> 00:08:32,200
You can't break through to.

171
00:08:34,500 --> 00:08:38,567
I know what you mean.

172
00:08:38,633 --> 00:08:39,674
Why didn't you tell that poor guy

173
00:08:39,675 --> 00:08:40,970
That his ex-wife is haunting him?

174
00:08:41,099 --> 00:08:42,567
Because I don't want
to make things worse...

175
00:08:42,633 --> 00:08:44,633
Roger's already got a ghost
in his house because of me.

176
00:08:44,700 --> 00:08:48,333
Besides, I need a little more
information, like how she died.

177
00:08:48,400 --> 00:08:49,797
Do you still think there's a chance

178
00:08:49,798 --> 00:08:50,798
that she could've moved on?

179
00:08:50,800 --> 00:08:53,133
I can hope. something tells
me she'll be here soon.

180
00:08:53,200 --> 00:08:55,133
Because this is where
I saw her yesterday.

181
00:08:55,200 --> 00:08:57,133
Which would tell us she's
still stuck in the loop,

182
00:08:57,200 --> 00:08:58,999
Still playing Suzie homemaker.

183
00:08:59,186 --> 00:09:01,233
I'm just wondering if her
imprint has something to do with

184
00:09:01,234 --> 00:09:02,800
mental illness and not her death.

185
00:09:02,867 --> 00:09:05,867
She's stuck in a loop because
she's loopy? makes sense.

186
00:09:05,934 --> 00:09:07,266
You're not helping.

187
00:09:07,333 --> 00:09:08,433
No, it does. really.

188
00:09:08,500 --> 00:09:09,966
People in the manic
stage of bipolar disorder

189
00:09:10,033 --> 00:09:12,266
Often have trouble assimilating
anything negative...

190
00:09:12,333 --> 00:09:14,800
Like being dead, for instance?

191
00:09:17,567 --> 00:09:19,999
That's the fourth person
you let go before me.

192
00:09:20,066 --> 00:09:21,999
I just need my husband's shirt...

193
00:09:22,066 --> 00:09:23,934
It's the blue one in the plastic,

194
00:09:23,999 --> 00:09:25,900
And I said no plastic.

195
00:09:25,935 --> 00:09:26,900
Hi.

196
00:09:29,667 --> 00:09:31,600
- Ok. 3 pieces.
- Thanks.

197
00:09:42,133 --> 00:09:43,966
Somebody help!

198
00:09:44,033 --> 00:09:45,300
Stop this thing!

199
00:09:45,366 --> 00:09:47,433
Somebody help!

200
00:09:47,500 --> 00:09:51,433
Tammy! stop it!

201
00:09:53,733 --> 00:09:56,913
Oh, I'm so glad you're
here!It's a blue shirt,

202
00:09:56,914 --> 00:09:58,500
and Roger likes light
starch if you could just...

203
00:09:58,567 --> 00:10:02,633
We are not gonna pick up
your husband's dry cleaning.

204
00:10:02,700 --> 00:10:04,567
You don't need to take
care of him anymore.

205
00:10:04,633 --> 00:10:05,834
It's time for you to move on.

206
00:10:05,900 --> 00:10:07,066
I can't do that.

207
00:10:07,133 --> 00:10:08,999
What would happen to my family?

208
00:10:09,066 --> 00:10:11,366
I need to take care of them, of Roger.

209
00:10:11,433 --> 00:10:13,133
No, you don't. they'll be fine...

210
00:10:13,200 --> 00:10:16,966
Stop it. Don't say that. Roger needs me.

211
00:10:17,033 --> 00:10:18,733
He has a new wife.

212
00:10:18,800 --> 00:10:20,700
Ok? he's moved on.

213
00:10:20,767 --> 00:10:23,133
You can let go now, really. it's ok.

214
00:10:23,200 --> 00:10:25,600
Why are you being so
mean? You helped me before.

215
00:10:25,667 --> 00:10:27,333
Why can't you help me now?

216
00:10:27,400 --> 00:10:29,200
Make those people listen to me!

217
00:10:29,266 --> 00:10:31,366
They can't. not anymore.

218
00:10:31,433 --> 00:10:32,586
The day that they stopped hearing you

219
00:10:32,587 --> 00:10:33,587
Was the day that you died.

220
00:10:34,166 --> 00:10:38,999
Look, you know, don't
you? what happened?

221
00:10:40,934 --> 00:10:42,867
Oh dear...

222
00:10:42,934 --> 00:10:45,533
There was something...

223
00:10:47,633 --> 00:10:52,077
It happened after I fell
asleep. I remember thinking

224
00:10:52,078 --> 00:10:55,166
It was strange how fast
I was falling asleep.

225
00:10:56,200 --> 00:10:57,867
And then what happened?

226
00:10:57,934 --> 00:10:59,467
I was floating.

227
00:10:59,533 --> 00:11:03,433
There was a big grassy field

228
00:11:03,500 --> 00:11:06,400
And lots of tall trees below me.

229
00:11:06,467 --> 00:11:08,233
My car was there.

230
00:11:08,300 --> 00:11:10,467
And colors,

231
00:11:10,533 --> 00:11:14,633
Lots of bright colors
flying all around me.

232
00:11:18,066 --> 00:11:20,934
Oh, no... I have to get home.

233
00:11:25,099 --> 00:11:28,433
Lots of colors? sounds
like a hallucination.

234
00:11:28,500 --> 00:11:29,834
Yeah or maybe not.

235
00:11:29,900 --> 00:11:31,834
She said that she was above a field,

236
00:11:31,900 --> 00:11:33,834
There were tall trees.

237
00:11:33,900 --> 00:11:36,400
She disappeared in October.

238
00:11:39,018 --> 00:11:40,459
Is this what you saw that day, Tammy?

239
00:11:40,460 --> 00:11:44,700
Kites? floating colors? Am I close?

240
00:11:44,767 --> 00:11:48,999
Hot? cold? lukewarm?

241
00:11:50,867 --> 00:11:54,533
Crap. need some dialogue here,

242
00:11:54,600 --> 00:11:56,700
A little back and forth.

243
00:11:56,767 --> 00:12:01,567
It's not so easy when you
have a client that's invisible.

244
00:12:01,633 --> 00:12:05,066
Ok, I've hiked far enough.

245
00:12:05,133 --> 00:12:07,966
And I draw the line at thistles.

246
00:12:13,366 --> 00:12:18,662
What's that? look, I'm sweating now.

247
00:12:18,663 --> 00:12:20,912
So if it turns out to
be another dead end...

248
00:12:59,700 --> 00:13:02,800
No. no!

249
00:13:03,700 --> 00:13:05,667
This can't be true.

250
00:13:05,733 --> 00:13:07,800
I can't be dead. not like this.

251
00:13:14,433 --> 00:13:15,599
I told my friend detective Blair

252
00:13:15,634 --> 00:13:16,731
that I found the body hiking,

253
00:13:16,766 --> 00:13:18,233
As opposed to breaking and entering,

254
00:13:18,300 --> 00:13:20,238
Which is how I found the last dead body

255
00:13:20,239 --> 00:13:21,239
That I called into her.

256
00:13:21,240 --> 00:13:22,361
How many times can you do that

257
00:13:22,362 --> 00:13:23,197
Before they haul you away?

258
00:13:23,198 --> 00:13:24,433
Well, they haven't locked me up yet.

